LOGICAL OPERATORS 

AND (Both conditions must be true)
Use it when you need a very specific group. 
For example, you want to find customers who are from London and have spent more than $100
SELECT email
FROM customers
WHERE city = 'London' AND total_spent > 100;

OR (Either condition can be true)
Use or when you want to broaden your search 

You want to find customers who came from either Instagram or TikTok
SELECT email
FROM leads
WHERE source = 'Instagram'
OR source ='TikTok'
;

NOT (Must not be true)
Use it when you want to exclude a group
For example, you want to see all of your subscribers 
SELECT email
FROM subscribers
WHERE NOT status = 'Unsubscribed';

BETWEEN (the range rule)
It is used to filter an inclusive range to target a specific group
Let's find all of our millennials so we can target them with relevant ads
SELECT email
FROM users
WHERE age BETWEEN 25 AND 35;

IN ( The list rule)
It allows you to specify multiple values in a single WHERE clause. It is much cleaner than using several or clauses

Find leads that came from your top 3 performing social media platforms 
SELECT email
FROM leads
WHERE source IN ('Instagram', 'TikTok', 'Youtube');

NOT IN  ( The exclusion list ruler)
It pulls everything except the values in your list. It is great to exclude entire regions or categories.

Example: Pull all of the information except the internal testing and international partners.

SELECT total_sales
FROM regional_reports
WHERE region_name NOT IN  ('international', 'internal');


